Jim Gilbert wrote:

&gt;Fredrik and all,
&gt;
&gt;I agree with the earlier posts.
&gt;
&gt;The one I have is strange because the seppa dai, kozuka ana and sukashi carving are very much like Kyo sukashi, but the thickness and folding are like a Ko-Tosho guard.  Ita plate tsuba with extensive sukashi work are usually attributed to Katchushi, and that&#39;s why I placed the guard on that page.  The iron is more like Owari than any of the above, though.  It&#39;s a strange combination, but each &quot;component&quot; is consistent with ca. late Muromachi.
&gt;
&gt;Your guard has a wider seppa dai, wider kozuka ana, thicker sukashi walls and a thicker plate.  It has a lot of rust and pitting that make it hard to see the surface but the unrusted areas look very flat and sharp.  Nothing about it points to an early origin, despite using the same design.  Without seeing it in person it&#39;s hard to say if it is a modern repro that has been intentionally rusted or an Edo period guard in poor condition.  I wouldn&#39;t be surprised if it&#39;s modern.  Thanks for posting your tsuba and thanks for the great responses.
&gt;
&gt;Jim
